<br>
The elf kept her thoughts on her destination in an effort to drive all else from her mind, but her memories always returned to the darkness of Neriak, the gathering of Innoruuk's faithful that she had attended two nights before.  Her fists clenched as she thought of that meeting, and of being dismissed from it.  As the thought of the Violent Harvest swept through her mind she snarled unconsiously.<br>
<br>
&quot;Damn them,&quot; she growled to herself, &quot;and damn that black-skinned bitch Creapiing to the darkest corner of the Abyss!&quot;<br>
<br>
As she made her way through the twilight forest, the elf replayed the events that had led her here in her mind.  Over and over the images played, and every time the drow scowled a little more fiercely.<br>
<br>
<br>
Kassy had left all she owned with the exception of a few spell components and the clothes on her back and made the journey from Qeynos to Neriak to meet with the Harvest.  They had something she needed: Knowlage of Innoruuk.  She had gone at the risk not only of losing all she loved, but of losing her very life as well, and she had been accepted into the dark family.  Let them think that she had come to embrace Hate, she knew that her heart yet rested with Tunare.  She said as much to them, repeatedly, yet they were blinded by darkness and heard only what they wished to hear in her words.  She didnt care, she would learn what she needed to.<br>
<br>
All that had changed when she had refused to kneel before an unholy alter in a place sacred to Innoruuk.  Kassy had stood her ground, lowering her eyes in respect as her mother and father had taught her when she was toddler, but no more. The Reaper had commanded her to fall to her knees before the sacred statue, and she refused.  Enraged, the Reaper had challenged the enchantress to single combat.  Kassy refused, saying that she had come to learn, not to fight.  She tried to explain that she would not, could not, kneel before an idol of the Prince of Hate, that she was not disrespectful and ment no sacrelige but could not do so and remain true to her own faith.  When she refused to kneel a second time, the Reaper had announced that she was anathema, banished her from Neriak, stripping her of all guild affiliation.<br>
<br>
<br>
Without noticing, Kassy had come nearly to the narrow pass that led to the Lavastorm mountains.  Only when the temperature began to rise noticably did she come out of her memories and look about her;  she was nearly to the mountains.  Ahead lay the last few stands of trees, withered from the heat, and she made her way toward them quickly, wanting nothing more than to be away from the accursed forest.<br>
<br>
With a final glare over her shoulder toward the dark city, the enchantress turned to step toward the mountains... and couldnt move.  Mocking laughter echoed through her mind.  Terrifying laughter.  His laughter.  Kassy felt herself slipping into unconsiousness and fought against it, but the world was quickly fading from her sight.<br>
<br>
&quot;You cannot escape me little elf.  You have been chosen.  Accept your fate, my Daughter...&quot; the words flowed like blackened, unholy water through her mind.<br>
<br>
As she lost consiousness and fell to the forest floor the dark elf gave no fighting words, no challenges.  She only reached for the medallian of Tunare that hung about her neck and whispered a prayer of a single word.<br>
<br>
&quot;Mother...&quot;<br>
<br>
*   *   *   *   *<br>
<br>
Kassy awoke sometime later as a soft rain dripped through the canopy of trees above.  She sat and brought her fingers to her brow, wiping her silver bangs away from her eyes.  The elf tried hard to remember what had happened, to walk in waking memory the steps she had taken in black unconsiousness, but found she could only grasp the image of wisps of gray, a fog that hid something far darker within it...<br>
<br>
Rising, the enchantress lifted her small pack.  I must get away from this place of Darkness, she thought to herself as she headed once again for the edge of the forest only a  hundred yards away.  Without looking back, she left Nektulos Forest behind her.<br>
<br>
*   *   *   *   *<br>
<br>
When the storm over the forest finally ended, all was still in the dark wood.  Neither animal nor insect moved about.  The only sound to be heard was the dripping of water as the trees shed their weight.  Weak beams of sunlight permiated their way down to the forest floor here and there, and one of these landed upon something that reflected the light back toward the covered sky.  Slowly, though the sunlight never changed, the reflection became fainter, as though the luster of the object was fading, until no more light shone off of it than would be reflected from an unformed mass of cold lead.<br>
<br>
The medallian of Tunare's Light faded completely, and the forgotten charm lay unnoticed among the dead leaves of seasons past.  Somewhere far away, the Prince of Hate's cold laughter echoed darkly.<br>
<br>
<br>
<br>
Kassy Lightborn<br>
Daughter of Tunare<br>
51st season Enchantress<br>
