<br>
They had fallen quickly before the nine trained bandits, and all the men had been slain.  Only one remaind alive of the caravan, and a far worse fate than death awaited the merchant’s daughter.<br>
<br>
As the moon rose, Jareden, a large human and leader of this circle of bandits rose from his seat at the fire and walked toward the bound and gagged girl.  He grinned down at her with rotten teeth and said it was high time the band sample her father’s wares.   Roars of laughter came from the assembled group of highwaymen but stopped suddenly as an explosion of light blinded them.  When they could see again Jareden was no more than a corpse, a large dagger cruely twisted in his gut.  Above him stood a single Tier’Dal.  The camp broke into chaos.<br>
<br>
A pair of half-elven females began to chant and roots sprang from the earth, grasping for the Tier’Dal’s feet, but she deftly avoided them spinning to the left.  Coming to a stop she raised her hands, chanting softly and the two half-elves fell silent and stood mesmerized.  Three down, six to go.<br>
<br>
A large barbarian came at her with a long curved sword but he had drunk too much and she easily dodged his attack and, speaking a word, called fourth dazzling colored lights.  The dark elf passed him, touching his temples with slender inky fingers and sent his mind sliding into chaos.  As he fell she caught the sword from limp fingers and spun around to face his companions just as the colors faded from the night air.<br>
<br>
The scimitar was heavy in her hand, but the balance was good and felt familiar.  She’d not wielded such a weapon in months, perhaps a year, but her childhood training had not left her when she had been cursed by the Father of Hate.  All wilder elves were trained in the use of such weapons from the day they could lift the dulled practice blades, and this elf was no exception.  <br>
<br>
The blade twisted in the air before her faster and faster as she summoned the swiftness of the wind into her swings.  Block.  Swing.  Parry.  Counter.  Remembered lessons came into her mind, Hartwood Master’s voice clear in her thoughts as she fought them.  She blocked the dagger of a human female and fell back a step calling the earth to aid her with roots to hold this oponent and the earth answered the call.  Trapped by the roots the bandit threw down her knife and held her arms wide in surrender.  The drow only sneered and spoke a word, melting the unfortunant human’s mind as her sword’s keen edge slid between her ribs.  Five remaining.<br>
<br>
One she rooted as she had done the dagger-wielding female, and left to suffocate by magic, another she dazzled with the colored lights before turning again to the troublesome pair of half-elven casters.  She smiled darkly at them as she drained them of their mental energies and still they just stood with unseeing eyes.  Her own strength returned by the spell she walked away from the three remaining bandits.  This had gone on long enough.<br>
<br>
The Tier’Dal stood on the outter rim of the firelight and closed her eyes.  When she had called fourth the spell that would end this little game she looked up, saphire eyes glinting with deadly light.  She pointed at the three with her scimitar and spoke a long string of words in the spidery language of Norrathian magic.   All three of the bandits returned to reality as they were thrown far into the air and screamed and they made the long decent back to the rocky ground.  A few seconds later the lone elf stood smiling darkly in utter silence.  The battle had lasted less than five minutes.<br>
<br>
The drow turned then, and stalked over to where the merchant’s daughter was tied.  Terrified, the girl shrank away from the dangerous elf as she approached but had no where to go.  Firelight sparkled on steel as the scimitar flashed out, cutting the bonds on the girls wrists and ankles with speed born of the wind then dropped to the ground at the girl’s feet.  Immediatly the girl backed away toward the fire and pulled the gag from her mouth but the dark elf did not advance.  Instead she stepped slowly backward into the darkness.<br>
<br>
Overcoming her fear the merchant’s daughter called out after the disappearing figure, “Who... who are you?”<br>
<br>
From the dark of night came the answer, “I was once called Lightborn...”  Then there was silence.  The Tier’Dal was gone.<br>
<br>
